{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T11:26:15.958218+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-07T01:45:56.358222+00:00", "id": 13471340, "conceptrecid": "13471339", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13471340", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13471339", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13471340", "metadata": {"title": "Functional diversity and trait filtering of insectivorous bats on forest islands created by an Amazonian mega dam", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13471340", "publication_date": "2023", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Abstract\n            \n              \n                \n                  Mega dams in lowland tropical forests often create large archipelagos, leading to biodiversity decay and disruption of ecosystem functioning in remnant habitat islands.\n                \n                \n                  We investigated the functional diversity and functional trait filtering of aerial insectivorous bats in both insular forest patches created by a vast ~30\u2010year\u2010old hydropower reservoir and the adjacent mainland continuous forest in Central Amazonia.\n                \n                \n                  Bats were surveyed using passive bat recorders across 34 forest sites. Based on a set of morphological traits derived for each species recorded, we estimated both the bat functional richness, functional evenness and functional dispersion at each surveyed site. We further assessed the effects of local vegetation, patch and landscape features on patterns of functional diversity. The interaction between functional traits, environmental characteristics, and species distribution was investigated using a combination of RLQ and fourth\u2010corner analyses.\n                \n                \n                  We found that mainland sites retained higher functional richness and lower functional evenness compared to forest islands, indicating a more complete functional assemblage in the mainland. Additionally, species composition was affected by local vegetation structure and forest area, with small isolated islands exhibiting pervasive loss of functional traits. RLQ and fourth\u2010corner analyses showed that larger understorey foraging species with greater dispersal capacity, constant frequency\u2013frequency modulated calls, and higher frequency of maximum energy were associated with more isolated small islands. Conversely, forest subcanopy species, exhibiting quasi\u2010constant frequency calls and presenting low dispersal capacity were associated with continuous forests and islands with greater forest area, and were therefore more sensitive to habitat insularization.\n                \n                \n                  Our study calls attention to the pervasive impacts induced by large dams on the functional diversity of tropical insectivorous bats. We recommend that future assessments of the effects of habitat fragmentation on mammals should include traits linked to ecosystem services. In designing and licensing new dams, we suggest the creation of extensive protected areas surrounding mainland forests to minimize the detrimental impacts of small isolated islands and safeguard the full complement of key ecological functions provided by insectivorous bats.\n                \n              \n            \n            \n              Read the free\n              Plain Language Summary\n              for this article on the Journal blog.\n            \n          , \n            Resumo\n            \n              \n                \n                  As megabarragens em florestas tropicais frequentemente criam grandes arquip\u00e9lagos, levando \u00e0 degrada\u00e7\u00e3o da biodiversidade e \u00e0 interrup\u00e7\u00e3o do funcionamento do ecossistema nos habitats insulares remanescentes.\n                \n                \n                  N\u00f3s investigamos a diversidade funcional e a filtragem de tra\u00e7os funcionais de morcegos inset\u00edvoros a\u00e9reos em manchas de floresta criadas por um vasto reservat\u00f3rio hidrel\u00e9trico de aproximadamente 30 anos e na floresta cont\u00ednua adjacente na Amaz\u00f4nia Central.\n                \n                \n                  Os morcegos foram amostrados usando gravadores passivos em 34 \u00e1reas florestais. Com base em um conjunto de tra\u00e7os morfol\u00f3gicos derivados para cada esp\u00e9cie registrada, estimamos a riqueza funcional dos morcegos, a uniformidade funcional e a dispers\u00e3o funcional em cada local pesquisado. N\u00f3s avaliamos ainda os efeitos da vegeta\u00e7\u00e3o local, caracter\u00edsticas de manchas e da paisagem nos padr\u00f5es de diversidade funcional. A intera\u00e7\u00e3o entre os tra\u00e7os funcionais, caracter\u00edsticas ambientais e a distribui\u00e7\u00e3o das esp\u00e9cies foi investigada usando uma combina\u00e7\u00e3o das an\u00e1lises RLQ e fourth\u2010corner.\n                \n                \n                  N\u00f3s descobrimos que os s\u00edtios de floresta cont\u00ednua mantiveram maior riqueza funcional e menor uniformidade funcional em compara\u00e7\u00e3o com as ilhas, indicando uma assembleia funcional mais completa no continente. Al\u00e9m disso, a composi\u00e7\u00e3o de esp\u00e9cies foi afetada pela estrutura da vegeta\u00e7\u00e3o local e pela \u00e1rea florestal, com pequenas ilhas isoladas exibindo perda generalizada de tra\u00e7os funcionais. As an\u00e1lises do RLQ e fourth\u2010corner mostraram que esp\u00e9cies maiores, que forrageiam no sub\u2010bosque, com maior capacidade de dispers\u00e3o, chamados de frequ\u00eancia constante e energia m\u00e1xima da frequ\u00eancia maior foram associadas a pequenas ilhas mais isoladas. Por outro lado, as esp\u00e9cies do subdossel da floresta, exibindo chamados de frequ\u00eancia quase constante e apresentando baixa capacidade de dispers\u00e3o, foram associadas a florestas cont\u00ednuas e ilhas com maior \u00e1rea florestal e, portanto, mais sens\u00edveis \u00e0 insulariza\u00e7\u00e3o do habitat.\n                \n                \n                  Nosso estudo chama a aten\u00e7\u00e3o para os impactos generalizados induzidos por grandes barragens na diversidade funcional de morcegos inset\u00edvoros tropicais. Recomendamos que futuras avalia\u00e7\u00f5es dos efeitos da fragmenta\u00e7\u00e3o do habitat sobre os mam\u00edferos incluam caracter\u00edsticas ligadas aos servi\u00e7os ecossist\u00eamicos. Ao projetar e licenciar novas barragens, sugerimos a cria\u00e7\u00e3o de extensas \u00e1reas protegidas ao redor das florestas continentais para minimizar os impactos prejudiciais de pequenas ilhas isoladas e salvaguardar o complemento total das principais fun\u00e7\u00f5es ecol\u00f3gicas fornecidas pelos morcegos inset\u00edvoros.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Colombo, Guthieri Teixeira", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Di Ponzio, Raffaello", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Benchimol, Ma\u00edra", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Peres, Carlos A.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Bobrowiec, Paulo Estefano D.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/91caa2104aad037156c0df47e8c6a745", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/87411b60b46200552f9a4cd493f8b4e2a68bf1335431127b401b0edf1418cc31", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/DHNPYX8P", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/DHNPYX8P", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/3e1b7e29b5ae03274889b2f1fbbd0672!/b215929-218396", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relat